title: Congreso sobre el Exilio Español Republicano
content:
Congreso sobre el Exilio Español Republicano

Descripción del Congreso: Titulado bajo los versos de Francisco García Lorca, el I Congreso Internacional sobre el exilio republicano español: “Cicatriz de la memoria, luz doliente de olvido” promueve potenciar el estudio y la investigación sobre los autores españoles que vivieron el exilio y que dejaron un legado cultural y filosófico imprescindible para entender la realidad española. La experiencia del exilio estuvo caracterizada por la intersección de aspectos contradictorios: de la victimización pasiva a configuraciones activas; del destierro involuntario a la diáspora como encuentro en nuevos contextos geográficos, políticos, sociales y culturales; de la amenaza a la integridad de la identidad personal a la multitud de maneras en la que los exiliados participaron en su reconstrucción creativa. Las ponencias y talleres, transmitidos en línea, pretenden no solo potenciar la incorporación de la investigación sobre el exilio español a los circuitos docentes, sino que abogan por reconceptualizar un nuevo discurso poético-literario irresoluto hasta la actualidad. 

From Wednesday, April 20, 2022 10:30 AM to Friday, April 22, 2022 4:30 PM EDT at Online.

title: Annual Symposium: "Translating Home: Views From the Diaspora"
content:
Annual Symposium: "Translating Home: Views From the Diaspora"

Please join us this Friday for our annual Art History Graduate Student symposium, “Translating Home: Views From the Diaspora,” set to take place April 22, from 10:15 AM to 6:00 PM! We are glad to be welcoming Dr. Emily Hue as our keynote speaker for the event.

The concept of home is unstable, bearing countless interpretations of physical and abstract places. Diasporic and transnational identities are particularly susceptible to the uneasy tension produced by slippages of stable meaning. Framed around both the abstract and material notion of home, Translating Home: Views From the Diaspora aims to interpret practices that span borders, fostering discussion that marks the complexity of real and lived experiences of those working in a transnational context.

 

Register in advance using the following link: bit.ly/3xJYJEU

 

 

From Friday, April 22, 2022 10:15 AM to 6:00 PM EDT at Online.

title: How to be Anti-Casteist
content:
How to be Anti-Casteist

Dr. Singh, author of Spotted Goddesses: Dalit Women's Agency narratives on caste and gender violence, has a PhD in comparative literature from Rutgers University. Her research focuses on intersections of caste, class, and gender in rural India as evident in the lives, indigenous leadership strategies, and oral narrative cultural expressions and published writings of Dalit women in South India and other indigenous communities of women globally. 

From Friday, April 22, 2022 4:30 PM to 6:00 PM EDT at Online.

title: PLEN Women in Public Policy Forum Sponsored by Marilyn Marolda Steiner DC'65
author: stephanie.perez@rutgers.edu (The BOLD Center at Douglass for Leadership, Career and Personal Development)
content:
PLEN Women in Public Policy Forum Sponsored by Marilyn Marolda Steiner DC'65

The PLEN Forum is a spring lecture series that invites women in politics and public leadership to educate students about their experiences. Held in conjunction with the political science course "Women and American Politics," students get a unique opportunity to hear and learn first-hand from women about experiences and paths to politics. This year's final forum brings together three amazing women who are working on critical policy issues for a special panel. Following the panel, participants will be able to hear from Douglass students who have participated in PLEN Public Policy programs throughout the year. A reception with follow. 

 

Panelists: 

Adzi Vokhiwa is the Federal Affairs Director at Giffords, the gun violence prevention organization founded and led by former Congresswoman Gabby Giffords. In this role, she manages and executes Giffords’ federal legislative strategy and works with Members of Congress and their staff to advance gun safety legislation

Aura Dunn was appointed to fill the Assembly seat vacated by now-Sen. Anthony Bucco in 2019, and a year later won the special election in the 25th Legislative District. Assemblywoman Dunn serves on the Assembly Commerce and Economic Development, Human Services, and Women and Children Committees as well as the Women’s Re-entry Commission. She also is a founding member of the New Jersey Legislative Disability Caucus, as well as serving on the New Jersey Human Relations Council and State Board of Canvassers.

Shanti Narra is the Middlesex County Commissioner Deputy Director. Narra chairs the County’s Public Safety and Health Committee. Since she joined the Board, she has maintained a strong commitment to provide the residents of Middlesex County with programs and resources that will ensure their safety and address their health and wellness needs.

From Wednesday, April 27, 2022 2:00 PM to 4:30 PM EDT at Ludwig Center.

content:
Design Challenge

On March 25th, the IDEA program will be kicking off a Design Challenge in collaboration with the Rutgers Center for Adult Autism Services and Prophet.  This design challenge is a mentored problem-solving experience that occurs over a 6-week period.  

 

The challenge theme is: How might we envision an inclusive campus climate to support the neurodiversity of Rutgers students, faculty, and staff?

 

The six weeks are going to work towards creating a "Future States" solution where you will work with physical materials (images, text, art, etc.) to create a shared vision for future experiences at Rutgers. If you are looking for a non-tech design experience, this design challenge will be more on the creative side, so it could be perfect for you!

 

No previous design experience is needed.  During the challenge you will work with professional Designers/Innovation Consultants to:

*Learn to conduct interviews and develop actionable insights
*Learn Design Principles
*Develop Future State Scenario solutions
*Discuss solution sustainability

If you are interested in this design challenge, please use this registration link to sign up!

From Friday, April 29, 2022 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM EDT at Rutgers Center for Adult Autism Services.

content:
Ecofeminism Presentation By DEI Ambassadors

Please join us and come to an event hosted by the Douglass Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion Ambassadors! The ambassadors will present their semester-long research presentation where attendees will learn how the climate crisis and women's rights are interconnected, define what ecofeminism means, identify activists/poets who have been instrumental in the ecofeminist movement and what contributions they made to it, and understand at least one way that ecofeminism is relevant to today–be it politically, environmentally, economically, etc. Students should attend to learn about a topic that is not widely talked about during a crucial time - we are currently going through a climate crisis and the rights of women are being attacked. Learn how these two current problems intersect and what you can do about them.

From Friday, April 29, 2022 4:00 PM to 5:00 PM EDT at Kathleen W. Ludwig Classroom 008.

author: rop@echo.rutgers.edu (Rites of Passage Ceremony)
content:
30th Annual Rites of Passage Ceremony Registration

The annual Rites of Passage Ceremony is a pre-commencement celebration to honor Black and Latinx-identified students who through resolute persistence have successfully completed an undergraduate or graduate degree at Rutgers University—New Brunswick. The event recognizes their accomplishments, hard work, and dedication, while simultaneously acknowledging the accomplishments of our student’s families and networks of support. Distinguished speakers, student awards, performances, and the incorporation of African culture and traditions—specifically the culminating Kente Stole presentation—all add to the vibrancy of this celebratory day.

Participation in the Rites of Passage Ceremony is open to all Black and Latinx-identified Rutgers University – New Brunswick Undergraduate and Graduate students who have earned their degree between January 2022 and August 2022. In order to participate, students must register by April 22nd, 2022 through the getINVOLVED portal. Only students who have registered by this date are guaranteed to be listed in the program and receive a kente stole. The late registration deadline is May 1st. All graduates are required to wear their academic regalia, which can be purchased from the Barnes and Noble Rutgers University Bookstore on Somerset Street. There is no cost to participate in Rites of Passage for graduates or guests.

All graduates who register by the April 22nd deadline will receive the following:
-1 Free Kente Cloth Stole
-1 Commemorative T-shirt
-1 Commemorative Program Booklet
-Unlimited number of guests
-Free access to the reception for graduates and guests immediately following ceremony

If you have specific questions about your registration or the ceremony, please email rop@echo.rutgers.edu.

From Wednesday, May 11, 2022 3:00 PM to 5:00 PM EDT at Jersey Mike's Arena.

content:
Douglass-ODASIS DOCTORS Living-Learning Community - Cohort 1

Welcome to the Douglass-ODASIS Community That Offers Resources and Support (DOCTORS) Living-Learning Community for Douglass-ODASIS undergraduate women of color pursuing allied health professional fields. 

The DOCTORS LLC provides a powerful set of programs to advance women in the sciences. Students are surrounded by peers who are experiencing similar changes and successes. Built-in residential support such as mentoring, tutoring, research opportunities and hands-on experiences empower women to persevere and succeed in STEM disciplines and careers. 

DOCTORS residents are encouraged to participate in the programs offered in the residence hall, meet regularly with the Graduate Mentors, and respect the academic environment of the residence hall. Additionally, Bunting-Cobb residents are strongly encouraged to engage in programs sponsored by the Douglass Project and the Douglass Residential College Community.  Becoming an active member of this community and participating in programs will help build your leadership skills, broaden your horizons, and encourage your academic growth.

From Saturday, September 1, 2018 12:00 PM to Sunday, May 15, 2022 12:00 AM EDT at Bunting-Cobb Residence Hall .

Study Opportunity to watch brief coping videos to learn ways to effectively manage many challenges during the COVID-19 Era.

Join a 12-week study to evaluate a quick way to learn how to effectively manage the many challenges as a Rutgers undergraduate in the COVID-19 era. Watch brief coping skills videos on your phone. Complete up to 4 surveys a day and 1 weekly survey (~5-20 minutes per day) on your phone for up to 6 weeks. https://kleimanlab.org/PhoneStudy
